{{List of coordinates}}
[[File:Otsuki-taisha torii.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]'''Kotsuki Taisha''' The main shrine"/>) is located in {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Ritto City|Q857310|WD=Q857310|1=Rittō, Shiga}}. In {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Divine Crest|1=UNKNOWN}} is "Kakudari wisteria" and "Maya no Usagi" <ref name="Shinja Agency">[http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=368 Otsuki Taisha] (Shiga Prefectural Shrine Agency). </ref>. The ``{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sanyare Odori of Omi Konan|1=UNKNOWN}}'' held within the temple grounds is designated as one of {{ill|lt=Furyu-odori|Q11665528|WD=Q11665528|1=Furyū-odori}} which is {{ill|lt=United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|Q7809|WD=Q7809|lt=UNESCO|1=UNESCO}}{{ill|lt=Intangible Cultural Heritage|Q84036549|WD=Q84036549|1=Intangible cultural heritage}}.

=== Enshrined God ===
* {{ill|lt=Rakubetsuou|UNKNOWN|lt=Ochibetsu no Mikoto}} (Ochiwake no Mikoto) <ref>Explanation board inside the precincts. </ref>
*: Also written as ``Rakubetsu no Mikoto'' or ``Sobetsu no Mikoto''. He was the {{ill|lt=prince|prince|WD=prince|ltq=Q12886381}} of the 11th {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|WD=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}} and the ancestor of {{ill|lt=Kotsukiyama-kun|Q11462129|WD=Q11462129|1=Kotsukiyama-kun}} ({{ill|lt=Kotsuki clan|Q11462133|WD=Q11462133|1=Ozuki clan}}). Depending on the literature, the notation ``{{ill|lt=Issokubetsu no Mikoto|Q11492324|WD=Q11492324|1=Prince Ikobayawake no Mikoto}}'' is also seen, but Issokubetsu no Mikoto is a half-brother of Ochibetsu no Mikoto.
* {{ill|WD=Q276944|lt=Okuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Oonamuchi no Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}
*: In the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, there was a {{ill|lt=Tendai sect|Q668188|WD=Q668188|1=Tiantai}} Gakuon-ji Temple (Kakuon-ji Temple) adjacent to the precincts of Otsuki Taisha Shrine; It is presumed that it was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=solicited|1=UNKNOWN}} and {{ill|lt=enshrined|Q11412524|WD=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}} from {{ill|lt=Hiyoshi Taisha|Q656451|WD=Q656451|lt=Hiyoshi Nishimoto Shrine|1=Hiyoshi Taisha}}.

``{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, there is one deity enshrined. At Kotsuki Taisha Shrine, two wooden seated statues of male deities (Denrakubetsu no Mikoto statue and Den Omi Taka no Mikoto statue) are said to have been made in the early {{ill|lt=11th century|Q7063|WD=Q7063|1=11th century}}, and by this time the enshrined deities were the current two.

=== History ===
The detailed founding date is unknown, but according to the shrine's legend, it was built in {{ill|lt=Ancient|Q41493|WD=Q41493|1=Ancient history}} in {{ill|lt=Kurita County|Q6446084|WD=Q6446084|1=Kurita District, Shiga}} (currently {{ill|lt=Kusatsu City|Q386677|WD=Q386677|1=Kusatsu, Shiga}}). Our company's origins date back to the time when {{ill|lt=Otsukiyama-kun|Q11462129|WD=Q11462129|1=Otsukiyama-kun}} (Otsukiyama-kun), a powerful family from the Ritto City|Q857310}} area, enshrined his ancestral deity, {{ill|lt=Rakubetsu-o|UNKNOWN|lt=Ochibetsu no Mikoto}}.<ref name="Kotsuki Taisha">[http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=368 Shiga Prefectural Shrine Agency Kotsuki Taisha]</ref>.Otsukiyama-kun was an ancient powerful family in Kurita County, and it is said that he also presented {{ill|lt=Uname|Q11644506|WD=Q11644506|1=Uneme}} to the {{ill|lt=Imperial Court (Japan)|Q30253177|WD=Q30253177|lt=Imperial Court|1=Imperial Court of Japan}}. In addition to the Kotsuki Taisha tumulus group remaining within the Otsuki Taisha campus, the surrounding area is the {{ill|lt=Shimotoyama Tumulus|Q60990033|WD=Q60990033|1=Shimotoyama Tumulus}} (a tangible {{jalink|cultural property designated by Ritto City)}. |Q858308}}), the Jiyama Tumulus, and the Oka Ruins (Kurita{{ill|lt=gunga|Q11643230|WD=Q11643230|1=Gunga (Japan)}} ruins) remain, and these are considered to be historical sites related to Kotsukiyama-kun. Based on these, it is assumed that Otsukiyama-kun was a member of the Kurita County {{ill|lt=gunji|Q4152149|WD=Q4152149|1=Gunji}} class. Otsukiyama-kun was {{ill|lt=Jokan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jogan|1=Jōgan}}15th year ({{ill|lt=873|Q30369|WD=Q30369|1=873}})<ref group="hara">"Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku" Article dated December 2, 15th year of Jogan (873). In </ref>, he moved to {{ill|lt=Heiankyo|Q751907|WD=Q751907|1=Heian-kyō}} and later served the {{ill|lt=Imperial Court (Japan)|Q30253177|WD=Q30253177|lt=Imperial Court|1=Imperial Court of Japan}} as the {{ill|lt=Kotsuki clan|Q11462133|WD=Q11462133|1=Ozuki clan}} ({{ill|lt=official|Q11452088|WD=Q11452088|1=official}} family).In {{ill|lt=Rokukokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|lt=Kokushu|1=Rikkokushi}}, the divine names such as ``Kojogami'', ``Kojogami'', and ``Shōjogami'' were used in the 5th year of Jogan ({{ill|lt=863|Q25052|WD=Q25052|1=863}}) <ref group="Hara" name="1st year of Jogan"/> {{ill|lt=Shinkai|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} was ranked Jugoinoge (Junior Fifth Rank) in 7th year of Jogan ({{ill|lt=865|Q30350|WD=Q30350|1=865}})<ref group="Hara" It is recorded that he was promoted to the upper rank of Jugoi (Junior Fifth Rank) in name="7th year of Jogan"/> and to the lower rank of Junior Fourth Rank (Junior Fourth Rank) in {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}}11 ({{ill|lt=911|Q24062|WD=Q24062|1=AD 911}})<ref group="Hara" name="11 years of Engi"/>{{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha Shrine (Heibonsha)|1991}}.{{ill|lt=extension (era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Extended|1=Enchō}} "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" established in 5 years ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) In the Kishiki Shinmeicho|Q11064932|Shinmeicho}}, "Kotsuki Taisha" is written in {{ill|lt=Ōmi Province|Q843882|WD=Q843882|1=Ōmi Province}}{{ill|lt=Kurita County|Q6446084|WD=Q6446084|1=Kurita District, Shiga}}, It is listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}} along with its associated shrine {{ill|lt=Otsuki Shrine|Q11462132|WD=Q11462132|1=Otsuki Shrine}} (currently {{ill|lt=Kusatsu City|Q386677|WD=Q386677|1=Kusatsu, Shiga}} Aochi Town). {Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha (Heibonsha)|1991}}<ref>The ``taisha'' in the company name ``Kotsuki Taisha'' appears to be to distinguish it from the Otsuki Shrine. {{Harv|About the mathematician Dr. Kotsuki Imao|2002}}. </ref>. The company name is pronounced as ``Wotsuki no Ohoyashiro'' {{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha (Heibonsha)|1991}}. Additionally, two wooden male god seated statues ({{ill|lt=Important Cultural Properties|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}) made in the early {{ill|lt=11th century|Q7063|WD=Q7063|1=11th century}} of the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} have survived to this day.After the Otsuki clan moved to the center, the head of the shrine was revered and renovated by the {{ill|lt=Aochi clan|Q11661125|WD=Q11661125|1=Aochi clan}}, who had a base in the vicinity, and the current inner palace of the main shrine was built by Motoji Aochi in October 1281|Q5537}}.<ref name="Kotsuki Taisha"/>. {{ill|lt=Yasunaga|Q980266|WD=Q980266|1=Kōei}} In April 2013 ({{ill|lt=1343|Q6072|WD=Q6072|1=1343}}), a four-legged gate was built by Shigeyori Aochi (although it does not exist, only the ridgepole was used as the main hall) {{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha Shrine (Shinouchi Shrine)|1981}}<ref name="Kotsuki Taisha"/>. According to "{{ill|lt=Sono Tairyaku|Q11422787|WD=Q11422787|1=Entairyaku}}" <ref group="Hara" name="Yasunei 3rd year"/>, in December of the same year, he was granted the ultimate rank of Shoichii upon the application of Shigeyori Aochi (Shigeyori Minamoto) {{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1981}}. After that, in {{ill|lt=Eisho|Q1193577|WD=Q1193577|1=Eishō (Muromachi period)}}16 ({{ill|lt=1519|Q6278|WD=Q6278|1=1519}}), the current main shrine (Important Cultural Property) was rebuilt by Makoto Aojima. However, the Aochi clan fell into decline during the {{ill|lt=Sengoku period (Japan)|Q204023|WD=Q204023|lt=Sengoku period|1=Sengoku period}} with the decline of the master family {{ill|lt=Rokkaku clan|Q2975342|WD=Q2975342|1=Rokkaku clan}}.In {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, in {{ill|lt=Keicho|Q1328185|WD=Q1328185|1=Keichō}}13 ({{ill|lt=1608|Q6758|WD=Q6758|1=1608}}) 3}} There was a donation of rice fields from the lord {{ill|lt=Ujitetsu Toda|Q3530228|WD=Q3530228|1=Toda Ujikane}}, and thereafter it was relieved by the {{ill|lt=black seal|Q11678034|WD=Q11678034|1=black seal}}{{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1981}}.

After {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, in {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|WD=Q7766|1=1876}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}9) {{jalink|Modern company rank system|Q712534} }, it was ranked as {{ill|lt=murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} and was promoted to {{ill|lt=gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in {{ill|lt=1881|Q7808|WD=Q7808|1=1881}} (Meiji 14)<ref name="Kotsuki Taisha"/>.

=== God level ===
* Record of {{ill|lt=Divine Rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} dedication in the {{ill|lt=Rokukokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|1=Rikkokushi}} era
** {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} 5th year ({{ill|lt=863 years|Q25052|WD=Q25052|1=863}}) December 3rd, Jugoinoge ("{{ill|lt=Japan Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}") <ref group="Hara" name="1st year of Jogan">"Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku" Article dated December 3, 863. </ref> - The notation is "Shojo God".
** December 5th, 7th year of the Jogan era ({{ill|lt=865|Q30350|WD=Q30350|1=865}}), from the lower junior fifth rank to the upper middle fifth rank (``Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku'') </ref> - The spelling is "Kojogami".
** October 9, {{ill|lt=Genkei|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 6th year ({{ill|lt=882|Q23824|WD=Q23824|1=882}}), from the upper middle fifth rank to the upper middle fifth rank {{Sub|Mama}} (``Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku'') </ref> - The spelling is ``Koshogami''. Is it a mistake of Shogoinoge? {{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha (Heibonsha)|1991}}.
* After Six Kingdoms History** {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} February 2nd, 11th year ({{ill|lt=911|Q24062|WD=Q24062|1=AD 911}}), Junior Fourth Rank Lower ({{ill|lt=Nihon Kiryaku|Q1053542|WD=Q1053542|1=Nihon Kiryaku}}) </ref> - The spelling is ``Koshogami''.
** {{ill|lt=Yasunaga|Q980266|WD=Q980266|1=Kōei}} December 2nd year ({{ill|lt=1343|Q6072|WD=Q6072|1=1343}}), Shoichii ("{{ill|lt=Sono Tairyaku|Q11422787|WD=Q11422787|1=Entairyaku}}") </ref> - The notation is "Kozuesha".

=== Precincts ===
* Main shrine ({{ill|lt=Important cultural property|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}) - Rebuilt in the late {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|WD=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. The roof is {{ill|lt=Japanese cypress bark|Q90373477|WD=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}}. The overall structure is simple but strong, with thick {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=wood splitting|1=UNKNOWN}} and few carved decorations, as well as old-style boat elbows for the kumihimo. The copy of the ridge plate and the ink calligraphy on the ridgepole mention that it was rebuilt by Makoto Aojima in {{ill|lt=Eisho|Q1193577|WD=Q1193577|1=Eishō (Muromachi period)}}16 ({{ill|lt=1519|Q6278|WD=Q6278|1=1519}}), and the style suggests that it dates back to that time. Along with the main shrine, two ridge plates have also been passed down, each marking the replacement of the roof in {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}}8 ({{ill|lt=1723|Q6921|WD=Q6921|1=1723}}) and {{ill|lt=Bunka (era name)|Q1373146|WD=Q1373146|lt=Bunka|1=Bunka}}12 ({{ill|lt=1815|Q6948|WD=Q6948|1=1815}}). A palace is placed in the inner sanctum of the main hall, and two wooden seated statues of male deities (Important Cultural Properties) are enshrined within the palace. The palace has an ink calligraphy dated to {{ill|lt=Koan|Q389180|WD=Q389180|1=Kōan (Kamakura period)}}4 ({{ill|lt=1281|Q5537|WD=Q5537|1=1281}}), which is older than the main shrine. This main shrine, along with the palace and two ridge plates (both designated), have been designated as important cultural properties.* The Hall - Built in {{ill|lt=1956|Q5221|WD=Q5221|1=1956}} ({{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}31). The roof is made of cypress bark.
* Worship hall - Reconstruction of {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}. {{ill|lt=Irimoya-zukuri|Q855025|WD=Q855025|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}}, the roof is tiled {{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1981}}.
* Ichino Torii - Built in {{ill|lt=1930|Q18787|WD=Q18787|1=1930}} (1930). Regarding the torii, there is an old record that it was built in {{ill|lt=Enkyo|Q1183728|WD=Q1183728|1=Enkyō (Edo period)}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=1745|Q7586|WD=Q7586|1=1745}}) near the current {{ill|lt=Meishin Expressway|Q904481|WD=Q904481|1=Meishin Expressway}}, and its foundation stone was relocated to Otabisho and is from the stone marker next to the existing <ref>Ichi-no-Torii. </ref>.
* Otabisho (Wakamiyasha) - Located in Oka, Ritto City, adjacent to the Oka ruins ({{ill|lt=Kurita-gun#gunga|Q6446084|WD=Q6446084|lt=Kurita-gunga ruins|1=Kurita District, Shiga}}) ({{Coord|35|00|37.81 |N|135|59|07.23|E|region:JP-25_type:landmark|display=inline|name=Otabisho}}).
* Kotsuki Taisha Tumulus Group - Within the precincts are {{ill|lt=circular tombs|Q11394747|WD=Q11394747|1=Round Kofun}}・{{ill|lt=Hangular tomb|Q11504353|WD=Q11504353|1=Square Kofun}}There are over 10 {{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha kofun group (Zoku kofun)|2002}}.** Mound No. 1 - The largest round tomb among the tombs, with a diameter of 25 meters. The stone remaining on the mound indicates the possibility of {{ill|lt=horizontal stone chamber|Q11543435|WD=Q11543435|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber}}{{Sfn|Kotsuki Taisha kofun group (Zoku kofun)|2002}}.
** Mound No. 10 - Located on the ridge west of our company grounds. It is a rectangular tomb measuring 15.5 meters from north to south and 13.5 meters from east to west, and is said to have been constructed in the latter half of the 5th century. {{ill|lt=1990|Q2064|WD=Q2064|1=1990}} ({{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}}2) and {{ill|lt=1999|Q2091|WD=Q2091|1=1999}} (Heisei 11) Excavations were carried out twice in 2002), and two split bamboo-shaped wooden coffins, an iron sword and a comb, and a Sue ware from the surrounding moat were unearthed. The details of the other burial mounds are not clear {{Sfn|Otsuki Taisha Tumulus Group (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}. The people buried in these burial mounds are believed to be members of the Otsukiyama clan.

=== Setsusha ===
* Yasaka Shrine (Gion Shrine) - Enshrined on the right side facing the main shrine.
* Hiyoshi Shrine (Sanno Shrine) - Enshrined on the left facing the main shrine.
* Inari Shrine - Enshrined next to the approach.
* Ryuosha - Enshrined on top of the Kotsuki Taisha burial mound.
* Outside company
** Junisho Shrine - Enshrined in Mt. Shimoto, Ritto City ({{Coord|35|00|17.43|N|135|59|28.81|E|region:JP-25_type:landmark|display=inline|name=Outside Shrine: Jūnisho Shrine}}). The precincts are said to be the site of Gakuonji Temple (Kakuonji Temple).
*** Shrines within the precincts of Junisho Shrine: Bentensha, Gionsha
