=== Main festivals ===
The annual festival held on {{ill|lt=May 5th|Q2550|WD=Q2550|1=May 5}} is commonly known as the ``''Kozue Festival''''. In ancient times, the first day of the rabbit was {{ill|lt=Uzuki|Q9092155|WD=Q9092155|1=Japanese destroyer Uzuki}}, but since {{ill|lt=1909|Q2057|WD=Q2057|1=1909}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}42), the funeral ceremony has been held on May 5th.<ref name="Shinja Agency">[http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=368 Otsuki Taisha] (Shiga Prefectural Shrine Agency). </ref>. The {{ill|lt=Hanagasa Odori|Q11615628|WD=Q11615628|lt=Hanagasa Odori|1=hanagasa dance}}, which is the main event of the festival, is currently held in rotation in five regions, but {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Eitoku|1=UNKNOWN}}2 ({{ill|lt=1382|Q6335|WD=Q6335|1=1382}}), the history of Ritto is said to have been carried out by an influential family called the ``Sakakimoto family'' in ancient times. Volume 4|1994|p=281}}.During the festival, a mikoshi (portable shrine) is carried in procession to {{ill|lt=Otabisho|Q11489117|WD=Q11489117|1=Otabisho}} near the Oka Ruins (Kurita Gunga Ruins), and Hanagasa Odori (Flower Umbrella Dance) is dedicated at several locations, including in front of the main shrine of Otsuki Taisha Shrine and Otabisho. The centerpiece of this Hanagasa Odori is a child actor wearing a charming costume, followed by an adult holding a kasahoko (flower umbrella), who dance and sing in a spectacular manner. This is said to be a modernized version of the Taiko drum dance. The Kozue Festival was selected as an intangible folk cultural property (selected intangible folk cultural property) in {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}} in {{ill|lt=1988|Q2426|WD=Q2426|1=1988}} ({{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}63) and was designated as an intangible folk cultural property (selected intangible folk cultural property) for which measures such as recording should be taken in {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. Volume 4|1994|p=281}}, {{ill|lt=2020|Q25337|WD=Q25337|1=2020}} ({{ill|lt=Reiwa|Q62609017|WD=Q62609017|1=Reiwa era}}2) includes festivals in Kusatsu City and ``{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sanyare in Omi Konan. The dance|1=UNKNOWN}} has been designated as a national important intangible folk cultural property. Cultural Affairs Council Report (Designation of Important Tangible Folk Cultural Properties, etc.)] (Agency for Cultural Affairs press release, January 17, 2020) </ref>. Furthermore, "Omi Konan Sanyare Odori" will be held on November 30th, {{ill|lt=2022|Q49625|WD=Q49625|1=2022}} (Reiwa 4).{{ill|lt=United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|Q7 809|WD=Q7 809|lt=UNESCO}}{{ill|lt=Intangible Cultural Heritage|Q84036549|WD=Q84036549|1=Intangible cultural heritage}} It was designated as one of the {{ill|lt=Furyu-odori|Q11665528|WD=Q11665528|1=Furyū-odori}}.

=== Cultural assets ===

=== Important cultural property ===
* Main shrine (1 attached palace, 2 ridge tags) (building)
*: Built in the late {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|WD=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. {{ill|lt=1958|Q5253|WD=Q5253|1=1958}} Designated on May 14, 1958 <ref name="Nationally designated main shrine">{{Nationally designated cultural properties database|102|1438|Kotsuki Taisha main shrine}}</ref>.
* 2 wooden seated male god statues (sculpture)
*: {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, early {{ill|lt=11th century|Q7063|WD=Q7063|1=11th century}}. Two statues, the Denrakubetsu no Mikoto statue and the Denrakubetsu no Mikoto statue. {{ill|lt=1997|Q2088|WD=Q2088|1=1997}} Designated on June 30, 1997 <ref>{{Nationally Designated Cultural Properties Database|201|5159|Wooden Seated Statue of the Male God (Denrakubetsu no Mikoto)}}</ref><ref>{{Nationally Designated Cultural Properties Database|201|5160|Wooden Seated Statue of the Male God (Dennen Omi Takamikoto)}}</ref>.
** The main deity statue, Denrakubetsu no Mikoto, is made of {{ill|lt=Hinoki|Q917187|WD=Q917187|1=Chamaecyparis obtusa}} wood and is 60.6 cm in height. His belongings, the scepter and scepter, were made of a different material, but they were lost. He wears a crown on his head and a vermillion robe.{{Sfn|History of Ritto Volume 4|1994|p=281}}.
** The statue of Omi Takamiko is made of a single piece of cypress and is 48.8 centimeters tall. His belongings, the scepter and scepter, were made of a different material, but they were lost. He wears a wide crown, a beard, and a green robe.{{Sfn|History of Ritto Volume 4|1994|p=281}}.

=== Important intangible folk cultural property ===
* Omi Konan Sanyare Odori - In addition to the Kozue Festival, it includes festivals in Kusatsu City. Designated on March 16, 2020 (Reiwa 2) <ref name="Reiwa 2 Notification"/>. Owned by the Kozue Festival Preservation Society. {{ill|lt=United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|Q7809|WD=Q7809|lt=UNESCO|1=UNESCO}}{{ill|lt=Intangible Cultural Heritage|Q84036549|WD=Q84036549|1=Intangible cultural heritage}} It has been designated as one of the {{ill|lt=Furyu-odori|Q11665528|WD=Q11665528|1=Furyū-odori}}.

=== Shiga Prefecture Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Properties ===
* Festival performing arts of the Kozue Festival - Owned by the Kozue Festival Preservation Society.

=== Others ===
* Mikoshi decoration phoenix and wig
*: Made in the Muromachi period. The phoenix and {{ill|lt=huawig|Q6386848|WD=Q6386848|1=Keman}} displayed on the {{ill|lt=portable shrine|Q979940|WD=Q979940|1=Mikoshi}} are both made of cast bronze. The former is 54.0 cm in height, and the latter is 16.7 cm in length and 15.5 cm in width {{Sfn|History of Ritto Volume 4|1994|p=315}}.

